  "opinion": "As a 18-year-old woman in Bologna working part-time as a waiter, I’ve observed how the gender gap in science isn’t just a statistic—it’s a lived reality. From my perspective, it’s the lack of visible role models for girls and women in STEM fields, especially in places like my city where science education often feels disconnected from everyday life. My parents both had solid educations, but my dad’s upper secondary background didn’t translate into a science career, while my mom’s lower secondary education meant she never explored STEM further. This gap isn’t just about numbers; it’s about the stories we tell ourselves. In Italy, where I’m from, science is often seen as a male-dominated space, and this perception starts early. I’ve noticed that in my school, boys are more encouraged to take advanced math and physics, while girls gravitate toward arts or humanities. The gender gap in science is also about access—there are fewer women in higher education science programs, and when they do enter, they face stereotypes that make them feel like they don’t belong. But I believe we absolutely should address it. As someone who’s curious and enjoys photography, I see how science and creativity go hand in hand. If we can show girls that science isn’t just about labs and equations but also about solving real-world problems—like how my camera helps me document environmental changes—I think we can bridge this gap. The key is to make science relatable and inclusive from the start, not just in classrooms but in everyday spaces like cafes or parks. We need to highlight women scientists who’ve made a difference in their communities, not just the famous ones in distant labs. It’s about changing the narrative so that girls see themselves as part of the scientific journey.",
